logistic=function(eta){
  k=exp(-eta)
  l=1/(1+k)
  return(l)
}

logit=function(p){
  k=p/(1-p)
  return (log(k))
}

curve(logistic(x),from=-50,to=50)

The logistic function image is (0,1), it is supported by the theory, indeed it is chosen to represent the probability of having a success given an X which produces that eta. Even from the graphic it is evident

As a consequence its inverse will have like domain (0,1)

curve(logit(x),from=0,to=1,n=500000)

Its image is (-Inf,Inf), obviously like the Domain of the logistic function.

  1. The function which describes the odds is the following:

Note that with n we are encoding beta0+beta1* x1++betap*xp

odds=function(n){
  return (exp(n))
}
curve(odds(x),from=-10,to=10)

We can observe as the odds, being a ratio between probabilities, have always a positive value. As they approach zero the denominator and so the probability of having a failure, will be higher than the probability of observing a success. On the contrary, as the odds tends to infinity, the probability of failure will be insignificant, with regard to the one of success.

If the probability of observing a failure and not observing it are equal, then the odds will be equal to one. As a consequence, the answer to the question is the value of y_hat that will make the odds equal to one, which is 0. Indeed the odds are simply the number of nepero powered to the linear prediction.

curve(odds(x),from=-1,to=1,xlab='linear prediction')
title(main='Odds of a failure')
abline(h=1,lty=2,col='grey')
abline(v=0,lty=2,col='grey')

odds(0)
## [1] 1
curve(logistic(x),from=-3,to=3,col='red',xlab='linear prediction',ylab='',ylim=c(-0.5,2))
curve(odds(x),add=T,col='blue',lty=2)
legend('topleft',legend=c('P[Y = 1|X]','ODDS(Y)'),col=c('red','blue'),lty=c(1,2))

As the values of the linear prediction goes to -Inf then the probability of having a failure increases, so that P[Y = 1|X]=E[Y] will become 0, which is an horizontal asymptote. In the meantime the odds will decrease until to 0, indeed as the probability of not observing a failure will be a infinitesimal of the probability of observing one. On the contrary as the values of n increases toward +Inf the odds will tend to +Inf, while the probability of observing a success will approach asymptotically 1. In 0 we have that the two probabilities are equal, so that the odds will be equal to 1 and P[Y = 1|X]=E[Y]=1/2.

  1. Odds(Y|X1=x1)/Odds(Y|X1=x1+1)= 1/exp{Beta1}=exp{-Beta1} Actually the function depends only on Beta1. Indeed, exp{-Beta1} is the factor by which the odds of observing a Failure are multiplied in case of recording a unitary decrease of temperature. Being Beta1 negative, this will result in an increase in the odds of having a success, which in this case is equal to:
exp(0.4166)
## [1] 1.516796

So observing 1 degree less in the temperature will make the Odds of observing a success 50% greater. exp{Beta0} is instead representing ODDS[Y = 1|X=0]. So the the odds of observing a success given that the temperature is equal to 0. In this case:

exp(7.5837)
## [1] 1965.889

The model suggests that observing a success with 0 degrees would be almost 2 thousands time more likely to observing a failure

Log Likelihood function

y=challenger$fail.field
x=challenger$temp
log_lik=function(Beta0,Beta1){
  n=Beta0+Beta1*x
  p=logistic(n)
  ret=sum(log(p^y*(1-p)^(1-y)))
  return(ret)
}

  1. From the experience learned in the previous practice we will use the following approach:

fitting a lasso regression to the logistic model in order to select a good starting model, which has been prived by insignificant variables.

The lasso will be used as initial model for the stepwise algorithm. This will have as scope a more saturated model, which will include as well some interactions, based on intuition. Doubtless we could as well include all the interactions, but being the stepwise selection a greedy alghoritm, enlarging so much the space of possible solutions would probably result in poorer performances. Besides the cost of the computation would be extremely high.

Lasso logistic Regression

x = model.matrix(g02~., health)[,-1]

For categorical variable the encoding is the following: namevark takes 1 if the original var=k, 0 otherwise. So for example sex2 takes 1 if the sex is female, as in the previous encoding female=2

y = as.integer(health$g02==1)

set.seed(7)

The additional variables dropped to 0 by the more heavier penalization parameter lambda 1se are: being a smoker, being a frequent drinker and being low-median educated. Nonetheless the first two variables are extremely counter-intuitive as being a smoker or a frequent drinker are known to be important feature in determining the health status. Regarding being a frequent alchol consumer, it is known from the descriptive analysis which there are very few cases in the dataset, so that the variable presents poor variability and so it is not very informative.

As our objective is to have an initial model which lacks insignificant variables we will use the 1se lambda.

SETTING THE FULL MODEL: We include in the matrix as well the interactions between age and alcohol or tobacco consume, as their effects are powered if the body of the subject is older. Besides, as we previously stated, from a medical point of view it is extremely strange that have been dropped down by the lasso (even though we had found a reason for the drink variable), as a consequence,it could be a good approach to test their significance in affecting other variables contributes,such age.

p=predict(final_mod,health_new,type='response')
cutoffs=seq(0.15,0.96,length.out=100)
n=length(y) 
metric=c()

for(cutoff in cutoffs){
  r=c()
  for (i in 1:n){
    if(p[i]>cutoff){r=c(r,1)}
    else{r=c(r,0)}
  }
  t=table(y,r)
  specificity=t[1,1]/sum(t[1,])
  sensitivity=t[2,2]/sum(t[2,])
  metric=c(metric,specificity+sensitivity)}

optimal_treshold=cutoffs[which.max(metric)]
max(metric)
## [1] 1.343322
r=c()
for (i in 1:n){
  if(p[i]>optimal_treshold){r=c(r,1)}
  else{r=c(r,0)}
}
confusion_matrix=table(y,r)

  1. If none of the predictors is significant, then the difference between D0 and D is asymptotically distributed as a Chi squared with p degrees of freedom. As a consequence we can formulate a test to verify that hypotheis.
summary_final=summary(final_mod)
stat=summary_final$null.deviance-summary_final$deviance
treshold=qchisq(p=0.95,df=length(coef(final_mod)))
stat>treshold
## [1] TRUE
p_value=1-pchisq(q=stat,df=length(coef(final_mod)))
p_value
## [1] 0

We strongly reject the null hypothesis and assume that at least one predictor is significant.

plot(final_mod,1)

the linearity relationship between the predictors and the response is completely respected.

plot(final_mod,2)

Normality is doubtless not respected but even a good logistic model could suffer from this condition, so that we cannot conclude nothing about its validity.
